{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.02,0.02,0.03,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78939"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4272"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64288"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"2082"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46504"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78939"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman undergoes an elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The procedure is uneventful, and six hours after the procedure, she complains of severe nausea. On examination, she looks comfortable, with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is some tenderness around the wound sites, but her abdomen is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metoclopramide (tablet)","Paracetamol (tablet)","Dexamethasone (tablet)","Promethazine (tablet)","Ondansetron (wafer)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOndansetron\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective 5-HT3 serotonin-receptor antagonist. This class of drugs is the most commonly used treatment and is considered \u0027gold standard\u0027 in the management of post-operative nausea and vomiting. The wafer form assists in administration as it dissolves on the tongue within seconds, making it easier for the patient to manage, rather than having to swallow tablets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiemetic that can be used for nausea, but ondansetron is often preferred due to its efficacy and ease of administration in wafer form.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E is a form of simple analgesia. Although it is likely to be charted post-operatively for pain relief, it is not used to reduce nausea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is a corticosteroid that can be used as an adjunct in preventing post-operative nausea and vomiting, but it is not typically used as a first-line treatment for acute nausea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromethazine\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in post-operative nausea and vomiting; however, ondansetron wafers are often preferred as they are easier to administer than tablets.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ondansetron is the gold standard treatment for post-operative nausea and vomiting.","Ondansetron wafers are preferred for ease of administration in patients experiencing nausea."],"references":["Schraag S. Postoperative management. Best Pract Res Clin Anaesthesiol. 2016 Sep;30(3):381-93. doi: 10.1016/j.bpa.2016.06.001. Epub 2016 Jun 9. PMID: 27650347. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27650347/","Stephenson C, Mohabbat A, Raslau D, Gilman E, Wight E, Kashiwagi D. Management of Common Postoperative Complications. Mayo Clin Proc. 2020 Nov;95(11):2540-2554. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocp.2020.03.008. PMID: 33153639. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33153639/","Gan TJ, Belani KG, Bergese S, Chung F, Diemunsch P, Habib AS, Jin Z, Kovac AL, Meyer TA, Urman RD, Apfel CC, Ayad S, Beagley L, Candiotti K, Englesakis M, Hedrick TL, Kranke P, Lee S, Lipman D, Minkowitz HS, Morton J, Philip BK. Fourth Consensus Guidelines for the Management of Postoperative Nausea and Vomiting. Anesth Analg. 2020 Aug;131(2):411-448. doi: 10.1213/ANE.0000000000004833. Erratum in: Anesth Analg. 2020 Nov;131(5):e241. doi: 10.1213/ANE.0000000000005245. PMID: 32467512. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32467512/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64288"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64288"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T11:56:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T11:58:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4272"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78939"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","